WEBVTT

00:02.330 --> 00:04.500
[ Andrew Simple's "New Day"
plays ]

00:04.500 --> 00:09.790
♪♪

00:09.790 --> 00:12.710
Richard: Most people believe
that who they are today

00:12.710 --> 00:14.960
is pretty much who they
will still be in the future.

00:14.960 --> 00:16.580
Hi!
[ Chuckles ]

00:16.580 --> 00:17.710
How was your flight?

00:17.710 --> 00:19.790
Ah, it was fine.
Thanks, Meredith.

00:19.790 --> 00:20.830
[ Chuckling ]
I mean, Maggie.

00:20.830 --> 00:22.710
[ Laughs ]
Maggie. Sorry.

00:22.710 --> 00:24.120
Someone didn't sleep
on the plane.

00:24.120 --> 00:25.620
Oh, I couldn't.

00:25.620 --> 00:27.580
I've rewritten my talk
at least 20 times.

00:27.580 --> 00:28.920
[ Chuckles ]

00:28.920 --> 00:31.170
Meredith is so sorry
she can't be here.

00:31.170 --> 00:32.710
Babysitter got the flu.

00:32.710 --> 00:34.420
Oh. Well, I'm glad
you're here.

00:35.790 --> 00:39.170
Our minds trick us into
thinking our entire history,

00:39.170 --> 00:41.670
every choice,
every change and chance,

00:41.670 --> 00:43.920
has led to this specific
moment --

00:43.920 --> 00:46.000
what we call "Now."

00:46.000 --> 00:47.250
You seem good.
[ Chuckles ]

00:47.250 --> 00:48.580
Chipper.

00:48.580 --> 00:50.750
Ah, I put my blood, sweat,
and tears into this PATH pen.

00:50.750 --> 00:52.290
I can't wait to
share it with the world.

00:52.290 --> 00:53.380
Mm.

00:53.380 --> 00:56.420
♪♪

00:56.420 --> 00:58.880
You're -- You're jumping too far
on the last one.

00:58.880 --> 01:00.120
I don't need your help.

01:01.960 --> 01:04.670
♪ It's a new day ♪

01:04.670 --> 01:07.170
♪ Whoo-ooh-ooh ♪

01:07.170 --> 01:08.670
♪ Whoo-ooh-ooh ♪

01:08.670 --> 01:10.920
Come on!
No, wait your turn!

01:10.920 --> 01:12.330
Yeah, cut it out, lads.

01:12.330 --> 01:14.830
Come on. Don't make me
regret bringing you. Let's go.

01:14.830 --> 01:16.330
Just missed it.

01:16.330 --> 01:17.380
Come on, guys.

01:17.380 --> 01:18.830
So close.

01:20.750 --> 01:22.710
Liam, look after your brother,
please, will you?

01:22.710 --> 01:23.580
Liam: Seriously, Dad?

01:23.580 --> 01:25.290
Come on.

01:25.290 --> 01:26.790
Dr. Hayes.

01:26.790 --> 01:28.290
I really hope I wasn't
supposed to bring my kids.

01:28.290 --> 01:29.580
No, their, uh, their
aunt lives down here.

01:29.580 --> 01:30.920
So...
Oh.

01:30.920 --> 01:32.290
...it's a chance for them
to see family.

01:32.290 --> 01:33.750
Well, I am heading
to something called

01:33.750 --> 01:35.170
Heart Valve Happy Hour.
Want to join?

01:35.170 --> 01:36.580
Is it as dire
as it sounds?

01:36.580 --> 01:37.880
Worse, somehow.

01:37.880 --> 01:38.880
But free booze.

01:38.880 --> 01:40.210
Maybe I'll see you there.

01:40.210 --> 01:41.960
Great.

01:41.960 --> 01:45.120
♪ That tomorrow
will be brighter ♪

01:45.120 --> 01:50.460
"It is a curiosity that has
driven humankind

01:50.460 --> 01:54.290
since the discovery of fire..."

01:54.290 --> 01:55.460
No. No.

01:55.460 --> 01:56.710
Oh.

01:56.710 --> 01:59.420
"...since the harnessing
of fire --"

01:59.420 --> 02:01.580
No.

02:01.580 --> 02:02.830
Yeah. Okay.

02:02.830 --> 02:07.040
"...since the taming of fire."

02:07.040 --> 02:08.250
Yes!

02:08.250 --> 02:09.460
[ Knock on door ]

02:09.460 --> 02:11.500
Oh, no turn down service needed.
Thank you!

02:11.500 --> 02:14.080
Catherine:
Richard. It's me.

02:14.080 --> 02:22.620
♪♪

02:22.620 --> 02:31.120
♪♪

02:31.120 --> 02:32.880
Aren't you going
to invite me in?

02:32.880 --> 02:35.040
I'm not sure I believe
you're really here.

02:35.040 --> 02:41.920
♪♪

02:41.920 --> 02:43.880
You here to buy
the convention center?

02:43.880 --> 02:46.830
Stop me from presenting?

02:46.830 --> 02:50.290
I'm here to stop
the foolishness!

02:50.290 --> 02:52.000
Richard, you said
you wanted an apology.

02:52.000 --> 02:54.210
Well, I am sorry.

02:54.210 --> 02:55.710
I am so sorry.

02:55.710 --> 02:57.710
Truly, for everything.

02:57.710 --> 03:00.710
I regret my behavior.

03:00.710 --> 03:01.830
Thank you.

03:03.210 --> 03:05.210
You don't have anything
to say back to me?

03:05.210 --> 03:06.540
There's nothing between
Gemma and me.

03:06.540 --> 03:08.120
Mm-hmm.

03:10.790 --> 03:12.500
I know what I saw.

03:15.170 --> 03:18.540
Well, something...

03:18.540 --> 03:20.040
almost happened.

03:20.040 --> 03:23.250
W-We went to breakfast,
and she kissed me.

03:23.250 --> 03:24.290
Oh, Richard!

03:24.290 --> 03:25.460
But I stopped her.

03:25.460 --> 03:27.000
But you didn't tell me.

03:29.580 --> 03:33.290
I...I didn't,
and I'm sorry.

03:33.290 --> 03:35.710
Oh, Richard,
we can fix this.

03:35.710 --> 03:38.000
You know we can.

03:38.000 --> 03:41.080
There are things in this world
you can't control, Catherine.

03:41.080 --> 03:42.880
And I'm one of them.

03:42.880 --> 03:44.250
I don't want
to control you.

03:44.250 --> 03:46.670
You bought my hospital,
for God's sakes!

03:46.670 --> 03:48.250
Because of your temper!

03:48.250 --> 03:50.380
Worst investment
I ever made.

03:50.380 --> 03:51.960
It's just
hemorrhaging money.

03:51.960 --> 03:54.210
The foundation board thinks
it's a sign of my dementia.

03:54.210 --> 03:55.420
[ Chuckles ]
I look like a fool.

03:55.420 --> 03:57.920
No, stop.
I'm serious.

03:57.920 --> 03:59.080
Oh, me too.
This is funny.

03:59.080 --> 04:00.170
This is not funny!

04:00.170 --> 04:01.790
You had a fight with
your husband

04:01.790 --> 04:04.920
and purchased an entire
hospital to get back at him.

04:04.920 --> 04:07.210
[ Chuckles ]

04:07.210 --> 04:09.000
Pac-North has
my name on it!

04:09.000 --> 04:11.290
[ Chuckles ]
My name!

04:11.290 --> 04:13.380
I mean, the worst place
I ever worked in my life!

04:13.380 --> 04:15.080
[ Laughs ]

04:17.120 --> 04:19.960
Oh, dear Lord.

04:19.960 --> 04:21.330
[ Laughs ]

04:21.330 --> 04:23.080
Do you think
there's a couple

04:23.080 --> 04:25.500
who ever had
such an expensive fight?

04:25.500 --> 04:26.500
No.

04:26.500 --> 04:28.920
Well, maybe
Anthony and Cleopatra.

04:28.920 --> 04:30.500
Ah. [ Chuckles ]

04:30.500 --> 04:32.290
[ Chuckles ]

04:32.290 --> 04:39.620
♪♪

04:39.620 --> 04:41.330
Come here and kiss me,
Cleopatra.

04:41.330 --> 04:42.960
Ohh.

04:42.960 --> 04:44.380
Mm.
Mm!

04:44.380 --> 04:46.000
Mm!
Mm! Mm! Mm!

04:46.000 --> 04:47.460
[ Chuckles ]

04:59.120 --> 05:00.580
[ Indistinct conversations ]

05:00.580 --> 05:03.120
Hey. How are you?

05:03.120 --> 05:04.830
Hi! Welcome to
Heart Valve Happy Hour!

05:04.830 --> 05:06.620
Oh. Wow. Yes.
Thank you.

05:06.620 --> 05:08.710
Uh, best party
of the year.

05:08.710 --> 05:09.960
Hey! Teddy!

05:09.960 --> 05:11.210
Oh, my God!

05:11.210 --> 05:12.420
[ Sighs ]

05:12.420 --> 05:14.000
You always see people you know
at these things,

05:14.000 --> 05:15.210
but they're never
people you like.

05:15.210 --> 05:16.710
Aww.
Here. I ordered one for you.

05:16.710 --> 05:18.250
Ooh. Thank you.

05:18.250 --> 05:20.000
Wow. They really splurged
for the reusable straws.

05:20.000 --> 05:21.750
[ Chuckles ]
I'm so glad you made it.
Mm.

05:21.750 --> 05:23.170
Evelyn rescued me.

05:23.170 --> 05:24.790
She's with Allison
while Owen's at work.

05:24.790 --> 05:27.080
You know, and for the first time
that I can remember,

05:27.080 --> 05:29.080
no one
in a 50-mile radius

05:29.080 --> 05:30.540
depends on my breasts
for survival.

05:30.540 --> 05:32.040
Mm. Cheers.

05:32.040 --> 05:34.080
Yes. Thank you!

05:34.080 --> 05:35.670
I know these things
are kinda lame,

05:35.670 --> 05:37.670
but I kind of
enjoy them.

05:37.670 --> 05:38.960
'Cause it's like
summer camp.

05:38.960 --> 05:40.670
For people who like
to cut into other people.

05:40.670 --> 05:42.170
I never
went to summer camp,

05:42.170 --> 05:45.120
but this is what I imagine that
the Olympic Village is like.

05:45.120 --> 05:46.670
Yeah.

05:46.670 --> 05:48.080
Assembling the greatest
talents in the world,

05:48.080 --> 05:49.710
putting them
in one building.

05:49.710 --> 05:52.330
Professional by day, but
screwing each other by night?

05:52.330 --> 05:54.790
Y-Yeah, I meant the "gathering
of the best of the best" part.

05:54.790 --> 05:55.960
Is that what
the Olympic Village is like?

05:55.960 --> 05:57.920
Totally.
[ Chuckles ]

05:59.000 --> 06:00.080
Oh, my God.

06:01.420 --> 06:02.500
What?

06:03.790 --> 06:04.830
Wow.

06:04.830 --> 06:06.120
I mean, he's --

06:06.120 --> 06:07.500
Do you know him?

06:07.500 --> 06:08.710
Yeah.

06:08.710 --> 06:10.250
Uh, no, no.

06:10.250 --> 06:13.790
I mean, not really.
We -- Uh -- Sort of.

06:13.790 --> 06:16.710
He was one of
my residents at Tufts.

06:16.710 --> 06:18.500
I-I doubt
he even remembers me.

06:18.500 --> 06:19.710
[ Glass thuds ]
God, he is so hot!

06:19.710 --> 06:21.080
Am I blushing?

06:21.080 --> 06:22.620
Maggie Pierce.
Olympic Village.

06:22.620 --> 06:24.290
Find out if he's single
and get yours.

06:24.290 --> 06:25.790
No, I don't do that.

06:25.790 --> 06:27.580
You don't have sex?

06:27.580 --> 06:28.920
I don't have sex
with strangers.

06:28.920 --> 06:30.790
You just said
you know him.

06:30.790 --> 06:32.790
Also...

06:32.790 --> 06:34.000
he's behind you.

06:34.000 --> 06:35.080
What? No. No.

06:35.080 --> 06:37.000
Mm-hmm.
Maggie Pierce.

06:37.000 --> 06:38.170
Hi...

06:39.380 --> 06:41.710
...you.

06:41.710 --> 06:42.880
You don't remember me,
do you?

06:42.880 --> 06:44.960
She remembers you.

06:44.960 --> 06:46.580
Eh, no. Yeah.

06:46.580 --> 06:49.170
Dr. Winston Ndugu.
We worked together at Tufts.

06:49.170 --> 06:50.920
We did.
Yeah.

06:50.920 --> 06:54.750
You know, I just remembered
my key isn't working,

06:54.750 --> 06:57.330
so I-I'm gonna
go get a new one.

06:57.330 --> 06:59.420
Three years
I've been coming here,

06:59.420 --> 07:01.500
and this is the first time
I've seen you.

07:01.500 --> 07:03.080
What -- are you
stalking me?

07:03.080 --> 07:04.290
[ Laughs ]

07:04.290 --> 07:06.960
[ Laughs ]
Not stalking you.

07:06.960 --> 07:10.170
But...seeking?
Yes.

07:12.000 --> 07:14.330
I'm gonna be a little forward
now. Is that okay?

07:14.330 --> 07:15.960
Mm-hmm.

07:15.960 --> 07:19.790
I have had a crush on you
since my first day of residency.

07:19.790 --> 07:21.960
But you were my chief,
even though I'm older than you,

07:21.960 --> 07:23.620
which just made me
crush harder.

07:23.620 --> 07:26.380
So, I bided my time.

07:26.380 --> 07:28.920
But then you went
and moved away to Seattle,

07:28.920 --> 07:30.540
right before I became
an attending,

07:30.540 --> 07:32.920
and I never got my shot
to ask you out.

07:32.920 --> 07:35.960
But I see that somehow

07:35.960 --> 07:38.290
you aren't wearing
a wedding ring.

07:38.290 --> 07:40.330
So, hopefully,
I still have a shot.
[ Chuckles ]

07:40.330 --> 07:43.460
Which is just
my long way of saying

07:43.460 --> 07:45.080
I'd like to
buy you a drink.

07:46.750 --> 07:48.580
[ Glass thuds ]

07:48.580 --> 07:52.170
♪♪

07:52.170 --> 07:54.420
♪ I'm gonna live it
like I own it ♪

07:56.420 --> 07:58.290
♪ Yeah, yeah ♪

07:58.290 --> 08:00.710
♪ Yeah, yeah ♪

08:00.710 --> 08:02.210
♪ Big city, bright lights ♪

08:02.210 --> 08:03.920
♪ Yeah, I like it ♪

08:03.920 --> 08:07.250
♪ Can't wait to see
where it goes ♪

08:07.250 --> 08:10.830
♪ Ain't nobody
gonna kill my vibe ♪

08:10.830 --> 08:13.080
♪ I'm gonna live it
like I own it ♪

08:13.080 --> 08:15.540
♪ Ain't nobody
gonna kill my vibe ♪

08:15.540 --> 08:17.380
♪ I'm on fire ♪

08:17.380 --> 08:19.540
♪ I'm gonna live it
like I own it ♪

08:19.540 --> 08:22.380
Okay, we only have 36 more hours
to get to know each other,

08:22.380 --> 08:24.170
so I'mma do
a lightning round, alright?

08:24.170 --> 08:26.580
Don't think. Just answer.
You ready?

08:26.580 --> 08:27.750
Ready.

08:27.750 --> 08:28.830
Favorite snack food?

08:28.830 --> 08:30.330
Pretzels.

08:30.330 --> 08:32.040
Wow.

08:32.040 --> 08:33.380
Failed your first question.

08:33.380 --> 08:35.250
How can I fail at naming
my favorite thing?

08:35.250 --> 08:37.420
Because pretzels are
only the favorite snack food

08:37.420 --> 08:39.670
of prisoners who haven't
had snacks in years

08:39.670 --> 08:41.830
and don't remember what snacks
are supposed to taste like.

08:41.830 --> 08:44.580
Okay. Well, I don't fail tests,
so give me another one.

08:44.580 --> 08:46.210
Favorite movie.

08:46.210 --> 08:47.580
"Amélie."

08:47.580 --> 08:48.750
Why?

08:48.750 --> 08:52.040
Because it's about
hope and resilience.

08:52.040 --> 08:54.500
Perfect day off.

08:54.500 --> 08:57.290
[ Sighs ]
Okay, sunrise run.

08:57.290 --> 09:00.040
Spend the morning
at a museum,

09:00.040 --> 09:02.170
the afternoon in a park,

09:02.170 --> 09:04.420
evening cocktails
by a body of water.

09:05.580 --> 09:07.580
[ Chuckles ]

09:07.580 --> 09:10.380
A nice dinner,
and then...

09:10.380 --> 09:13.670
ice cream while
walking through the city.

09:13.670 --> 09:15.920
Bed early, with a book.

09:15.920 --> 09:18.880
So, your perfect night
is a romantic comedy.

09:18.880 --> 09:20.120
Okay.
[ Chuckles ]

09:20.120 --> 09:22.000
No, I didn't say who
I was doing all of that with.

09:22.000 --> 09:23.460
Well, who are you
doing all that with?

09:23.460 --> 09:24.920
Me.

09:24.920 --> 09:26.790
So, you like
being alone?

09:26.790 --> 09:28.750
I do.

09:28.750 --> 09:30.500
To a point.

09:30.500 --> 09:31.880
Favorite movie.

09:31.880 --> 09:32.960
"Ghostbusters."

09:34.880 --> 09:36.330
Perfect day off.

09:36.330 --> 09:37.920
Wake up...

09:37.920 --> 09:39.710
well after sunrise.

09:39.710 --> 09:41.170
[ Chuckles ]

09:41.170 --> 09:44.920
Roll over to
the beautiful heart surgeon

09:44.920 --> 09:46.920
in bed beside me.

09:46.920 --> 09:50.210
Do that thing to her
that makes her lower back arch.

09:59.040 --> 10:00.830
[ Inhales sharply ]

10:08.670 --> 10:10.040
Okay.

10:11.670 --> 10:13.460
No more lightning round.

10:13.460 --> 10:14.710
[ Clears throat ]

10:14.710 --> 10:17.750
Who is your favorite person
in the whole world?

10:17.750 --> 10:18.710
My mom.

10:19.920 --> 10:22.330
She was my protector.

10:23.540 --> 10:27.000
She was
this fierce mama lion.

10:27.000 --> 10:29.750
She didn't let anyone
mess with me.

10:29.750 --> 10:31.710
Including my dad.

10:31.710 --> 10:33.170
She died...

10:35.040 --> 10:37.710
...about two years ago.

10:37.710 --> 10:39.330
Ovarian cancer.

10:39.330 --> 10:40.670
Oh, my God.

10:40.670 --> 10:42.170
Yeah.

10:42.170 --> 10:45.290
It happened really fast.

10:45.290 --> 10:47.960
My mom died
two years ago.

10:47.960 --> 10:49.750
Breast cancer.

10:49.750 --> 10:51.460
No, actually, it was
three years ago.

10:51.460 --> 10:53.250
God.

10:53.250 --> 10:55.880
I can't believe
it's been that long.

10:55.880 --> 10:57.580
There's nothing worse
than watching

10:57.580 --> 10:59.710
the woman who protected you
from the world

10:59.710 --> 11:01.710
get sicker and sicker

11:01.710 --> 11:04.420
and you not be able
to fix her.

11:07.080 --> 11:09.790
Okay, so...

11:09.790 --> 11:11.080
do you do this?

11:11.080 --> 11:14.790
Do you have
med conference flings?

11:14.790 --> 11:17.920
I can't say that I've never
hooked up at one of these.

11:17.920 --> 11:21.620
But I've never done this.

11:21.620 --> 11:23.250
What's this?

11:23.250 --> 11:26.620
Falling this hard
in one night.

11:29.580 --> 11:31.120
Me neither.

11:31.120 --> 11:32.330
♪♪

11:37.960 --> 11:40.040
These conferences
are all the same.

11:40.040 --> 11:42.790
Yep. Just
a sea of desperation.

11:42.790 --> 11:45.000
Sales reps trying
to unload their equipment

11:45.000 --> 11:46.420
before it becomes
obsolete.

11:46.420 --> 11:47.790
Or banned.

11:47.790 --> 11:49.380
Wow. Really sounds
like your scene.

11:49.380 --> 11:50.920
If you hate it so much,
why'd you come?

11:50.920 --> 11:52.830
Well, I'm the new guy.

11:52.830 --> 11:55.120
And Bailey asked me
to come represent peds.

11:55.120 --> 11:58.210
Didn't seem like an invitation
I should turn down.

11:58.210 --> 12:00.120
The boys get to see
their aunt, so...

12:00.120 --> 12:01.790
Which is your sister or...

12:01.790 --> 12:02.710
Sister-in-law.

12:02.710 --> 12:03.620
Mm.

12:03.620 --> 12:05.170
Evening, doctors.

12:05.170 --> 12:07.250
Dane Pinetti.
I'm with Wilkes and Boon.

12:07.250 --> 12:10.170
Teddy Altman.
Grey-Sloan. In Seattle.

12:10.170 --> 12:12.120
[ Ice rattles ]

12:12.120 --> 12:15.210
You look like a man
in need of something.

12:15.210 --> 12:17.420
Do I?
And what might that be?

12:19.580 --> 12:20.920
Hmm.

12:20.920 --> 12:22.790
Not quite sure what
to make of this.

12:22.790 --> 12:25.620
Well, you, uh...

12:25.620 --> 12:28.000
you click the little part
at the back,

12:28.000 --> 12:30.000
and you write
with the front.

12:30.000 --> 12:32.500
Mm.
It's called a pen.

12:32.500 --> 12:34.380
Courtesy of Thrivea,

12:34.380 --> 12:36.000
who make erectile
dysfunction medication.

12:36.000 --> 12:37.670
[ Chuckles ] They do?

12:37.670 --> 12:39.580
You don't even know
what your own company makes?

12:39.580 --> 12:41.000
My friend said
a company at a convention

12:41.000 --> 12:42.330
was paying 500 bucks,

12:42.330 --> 12:44.170
and all I had to do
was hand out pens and smile.

12:44.170 --> 12:45.290
[ Chuckles ]

12:45.290 --> 12:47.420
That might not sound
like much to a doctor,

12:47.420 --> 12:50.420
but to a starving artist,
that's rent.

12:50.420 --> 12:52.960
Oh. No wonder no guys
want these pens.

12:52.960 --> 12:55.830
[ Chuckles ]

12:55.830 --> 12:57.000
What kind of artist?

12:57.000 --> 12:58.420
Apart from starving?

12:58.420 --> 12:59.960
Mixed media.

12:59.960 --> 13:02.290
A lot of multiple exposures
and instant film transfers.

13:02.290 --> 13:03.750
Mm.

13:03.750 --> 13:05.880
That doesn't make any sense
to you, does it?

13:05.880 --> 13:07.250
No, the individual
words do --

13:07.250 --> 13:08.540
just not when you
put them together.

13:08.540 --> 13:10.080
[ Laughs ]

13:10.080 --> 13:12.420
So, what are you
drinking?

13:12.420 --> 13:13.750
I'd like to.

13:13.750 --> 13:17.040
But these are not gonna
hand themselves out.

13:17.040 --> 13:18.580
Well...

13:20.420 --> 13:21.790
I go through
a lot of pens.

13:23.790 --> 13:24.830
So, how about that drink?

13:27.580 --> 13:29.330
Obama:
Watching the debates...

13:29.330 --> 13:31.250
They said just
a couple more minutes.

13:31.250 --> 13:32.790
[ Indistinct talking on TV ]

13:32.790 --> 13:34.330
Okay. [ Sighs ]

13:34.330 --> 13:36.710
This is happening.

13:36.710 --> 13:40.500
Are you sure they don't need
a few more, like, years?

13:40.500 --> 13:41.830
Babe, this is --

13:41.830 --> 13:45.000
A hysterectomy
on a 33-year-old.

13:45.000 --> 13:46.880
They're removing
an important part of me.

13:46.880 --> 13:48.750
And if you say
"Not a big deal,"

13:48.750 --> 13:50.830
I am going to kill you --
in front of our sons --

13:50.830 --> 13:52.420
and it will
be your fault.

13:52.420 --> 13:54.170
I was gonna say "routine,"
but...

13:54.170 --> 13:56.040
[ Video games beeping ]

13:56.040 --> 13:57.460
The surgeon we found --

13:57.460 --> 13:59.080
she's done more of these
than I can even count.

13:59.080 --> 14:01.710
She's minimally invasive,
fast recovery time,

14:01.710 --> 14:03.330
low post-op
complications.

14:03.330 --> 14:05.580
You're in amazing hands.
She's great, really.

14:05.580 --> 14:08.290
Or I'll bleed out
or she'll cut into my bladder

14:08.290 --> 14:11.290
or I'll get a horrible
infection and die.

14:11.290 --> 14:15.120
Well, in that case,
me and the boys will move on.

14:15.120 --> 14:17.540
Don't get me wrong --
it'll be a tough couple of days.

14:17.540 --> 14:20.710
Then single women will start
showing up with casseroles.

14:20.710 --> 14:23.330
I mean, I won't even have to
try. They'll feel so bad for me.

14:23.330 --> 14:25.170
Ohh.
I mean...surgeon.

14:25.170 --> 14:26.750
[ Laughs ]
Sexy widower.

14:26.750 --> 14:28.460
Single dad.

14:28.460 --> 14:29.960
I mean, I'll be -- I'll be
batting them away, honestly.

14:29.960 --> 14:31.500
Uh-huh. Right.

14:31.500 --> 14:32.620
I hate you.

14:32.620 --> 14:34.080
I love you.

14:36.290 --> 14:39.040
Mrs. Douglas at school
had skin cancer,

14:39.040 --> 14:40.920
and she's fine now.

14:40.920 --> 14:43.710
That's
a different cancer.

14:43.710 --> 14:45.710
Oh.

14:45.710 --> 14:49.460
But that's really nice
to hear, honey.

14:49.460 --> 14:52.750
Hey, could you boys
go find Mommy a ginger ale?

14:52.750 --> 14:54.460
It'll make me
feel better.
Okay.

14:54.460 --> 15:02.540
♪♪

15:02.540 --> 15:05.290
[ Sniffles ]

15:05.290 --> 15:06.920
Mrs. Douglas is the one
who accused him of

15:06.920 --> 15:08.790
writing swear words
on his desk.

15:08.790 --> 15:10.250
She's a monster.

15:10.250 --> 15:12.210
I need you
to listen to me.

15:12.210 --> 15:13.750
The nurse should be
here by now.

15:13.750 --> 15:15.120
If this doesn't work...

15:16.380 --> 15:18.380
It has to work.

15:18.380 --> 15:21.960
It's the second
clinical trial we've tried.

15:21.960 --> 15:24.330
We're at the end of this.
I'm not gonna be okay.

15:25.620 --> 15:28.580
I've seen people bounce back
from far worse than this.

15:28.580 --> 15:32.210
It is likely that you're gonna
be doing this alone soon,

15:32.210 --> 15:33.750
so I need you to listen.

15:34.960 --> 15:37.080
No.

15:37.080 --> 15:38.500
I'm not.

15:38.500 --> 15:43.170
Make sure the boys know
it's okay to cry.

15:43.170 --> 15:44.920
To feel it.

15:44.920 --> 15:47.330
To feel everything.

15:47.330 --> 15:49.210
I don't want them
locking this up

15:49.210 --> 15:51.710
and letting it
eat away at them.

15:51.710 --> 15:53.500
Don't be strong.

15:53.500 --> 15:54.750
[ Sniffles ]

15:54.750 --> 15:56.880
Be a mess.

15:56.880 --> 15:59.500
Let them know that
it's okay to fall apart.

15:59.500 --> 16:01.750
[ Voice breaking ]
Please don't do this.

16:01.750 --> 16:04.920
And promise me that you're gonna
let the boys see my sister.

16:04.920 --> 16:06.460
♪ ...glory, Lord ♪

16:06.460 --> 16:11.170
I know she's crazy,
but she's not a bad person.

16:11.170 --> 16:13.290
And she loves them.

16:13.290 --> 16:14.460
[ Exhales shakily ]

16:14.460 --> 16:16.380
And whenever you have
trouble with them,

16:16.380 --> 16:17.960
just call your mother.

16:17.960 --> 16:19.170
[ Chuckles, sniffles ]

16:19.170 --> 16:21.290
You are proof

16:21.290 --> 16:23.960
that she knows
what she's doing.

16:25.170 --> 16:27.920
And it's okay
if Austin quits piano.

16:27.920 --> 16:29.500
Yeah.

16:29.500 --> 16:32.170
I told him that he'll get better
if he keeps practicing,

16:32.170 --> 16:34.670
but...I think
it's hopeless.

16:34.670 --> 16:37.580
[ Laughs, sniffles ]

16:37.580 --> 16:40.790
And -- And -- And keep an eye
on Liam's temper.

16:40.790 --> 16:44.380
'Cause I think
he gets it from me.

16:44.380 --> 16:47.080
And we've both seen
the mess that can cause.

16:47.080 --> 16:49.380
♪ And it feels like glory... ♪

16:49.380 --> 16:53.790
And it's okay for you
to fall in love again.

16:53.790 --> 16:55.500
You have my permission.

16:55.500 --> 16:58.170
[ Sobs ]

16:58.170 --> 17:00.380
I don't want that.

17:00.380 --> 17:05.120
Which is why you need
to hear me say that it is okay.

17:05.120 --> 17:10.000
You don't need to
beat yourself up or feel guilty.

17:10.000 --> 17:13.080
♪ There'll be oceans
to wonder for miles ♪

17:13.080 --> 17:16.460
You deserve to be happy.

17:16.460 --> 17:19.830
♪ There'll be flowers
and roses so ♪

17:19.830 --> 17:21.330
[ Sniffles ]

17:21.330 --> 17:24.210
Bright side, you won't
have to work for it.

17:24.210 --> 17:25.670
[ Chuckles ]

17:25.670 --> 17:31.290
Sexy widower,
surgeon, single dad.

17:31.290 --> 17:32.620
[ Sniffles ]

17:32.620 --> 17:34.540
You'll be
batting them away.

17:34.540 --> 17:36.210
♪ Let them notice ♪

17:36.210 --> 17:37.880
♪ It's in your heart now ♪

17:37.880 --> 17:39.540
♪ And it feels like ♪

17:39.540 --> 17:41.330
♪ It's in your heart now ♪

17:41.330 --> 17:43.080
♪ Let them notice ♪

17:43.080 --> 17:44.880
♪ It's in your heart now ♪

17:44.880 --> 17:51.040
♪ And it feels like glory,
Lord ♪

17:56.670 --> 17:58.920
[ Sniffles ]

17:58.920 --> 18:02.290
Okay, lads.
That's everything.

18:02.290 --> 18:04.080
Austin: [ Voice breaking ]
Can we stay?

18:04.080 --> 18:06.330
A little longer?

18:06.330 --> 18:07.830
That's creepy.

18:07.830 --> 18:09.080
[ Sniffles ]

18:09.080 --> 18:11.170
Oh, no, Austin.
Here.

18:11.170 --> 18:12.830
It's okay.

18:12.830 --> 18:15.120
♪♪

18:15.120 --> 18:16.380
[ Sniffles ]

18:16.380 --> 18:18.000
We can stay
as long as you want.

18:19.420 --> 18:21.710
Austin: I want Mama.
[ Sniffles ]

18:21.710 --> 18:23.960
[ Sighs ] Me too.

18:23.960 --> 18:28.580
♪♪

18:28.580 --> 18:30.710
[ Sniffles ]

18:30.710 --> 18:32.120
[ Crying ]

18:32.120 --> 18:37.250
♪♪

18:37.250 --> 18:38.880
Come here.

18:38.880 --> 18:43.040
♪♪

18:44.000 --> 18:45.670
Mm.
Did you order these?

18:45.670 --> 18:46.710
Guilty.

18:48.420 --> 18:50.420
Do you always sell this hard
to everyone here?

18:50.420 --> 18:51.710
Well, not everyone here

18:51.710 --> 18:54.080
works for Catherine Fox's
flagship hospital.

18:54.080 --> 18:56.460
Maybe you should
take up your business with her.

18:56.460 --> 18:57.830
You know how hard it is to get
face time with that woman?

18:57.830 --> 18:59.210
Mm.

18:59.210 --> 19:00.830
Listen, this is a really
exciting opportunity.

19:00.830 --> 19:02.920
Wilkes and Boon is
looking to expand R&D

19:02.920 --> 19:04.380
beyond our laboratories.

19:04.380 --> 19:06.170
We want to partner with
the right hospital

19:06.170 --> 19:08.080
and develop side by side
with you.

19:08.080 --> 19:09.210
That actually
could be something --

19:09.210 --> 19:11.250
I know all about
your devices.

19:11.250 --> 19:12.920
I know about
the c-30 power morcellator.

19:12.920 --> 19:14.620
Do you know about
that one, Dane?

19:14.620 --> 19:17.000
Of course. It's our most
popular model on the market.

19:17.000 --> 19:18.710
I bet you'll say
it's magic.

19:18.710 --> 19:20.330
What is it?

19:20.330 --> 19:22.170
It allows for minimally
invasive hysterectomies.

19:22.170 --> 19:24.620
Its little spinning claws
chop up fibroids,

19:24.620 --> 19:25.920
make them disappear.

19:25.920 --> 19:27.250
But there's a problem.

19:29.960 --> 19:31.920
This fibroid...

19:31.920 --> 19:33.540
isn't a fibroid.

19:33.540 --> 19:34.920
It's cancer.

19:34.920 --> 19:37.420
But there's no way
of knowing that before you cut.

19:37.420 --> 19:39.960
And along comes
your morcellator, and...

19:39.960 --> 19:41.120
[ Loud thud ]

19:41.120 --> 19:42.830
What...the hell, man?

19:42.830 --> 19:44.290
What started out

19:44.290 --> 19:47.000
as nicely contained,
easily removable

19:47.000 --> 19:49.250
has now spread
countless cancer cells

19:49.250 --> 19:51.040
all throughout
the patient's body.

19:51.040 --> 19:55.460
Cancer that metastasizes
and grows and can't be stopped.

19:55.460 --> 20:00.000
Less than 1% of benign fibroids
turn into uterine sarcomas.

20:00.000 --> 20:03.620
My wife was
one of those 1%.

20:03.620 --> 20:06.080
Her name was Abigail.

20:06.080 --> 20:08.580
Your device took her.

20:08.580 --> 20:10.580
It took the mother
of my sons.

20:10.580 --> 20:12.290
And you still sell
the thing,

20:12.290 --> 20:13.880
even though you know
it can kill,

20:13.880 --> 20:15.460
and you pay
to suppress the proof.

20:15.460 --> 20:16.420
So, no.

20:16.420 --> 20:17.670
[ Thud ]

20:17.670 --> 20:20.170
I don't want your drink.

20:20.170 --> 20:22.000
And you're lucky
I haven't already put that pen

20:22.000 --> 20:23.210
through your throat.

20:24.580 --> 20:25.920
O-Okay.

20:25.920 --> 20:32.540
♪♪

20:32.540 --> 20:34.710
Apologies, Dr. Altman.

20:34.710 --> 20:38.330
♪♪

20:44.170 --> 20:47.830
♪ Lazy days, dreaming
in the midday sun ♪

20:47.830 --> 20:52.620
♪ Miles away, you're thinking
about the things I've done ♪

20:52.620 --> 20:53.830
Teddy?

20:53.830 --> 20:56.670
♪ Time to hit the road again ♪

20:56.670 --> 20:58.120
♪♪

20:58.120 --> 21:01.080
Reporter: ...been
a second explosion, uh,

21:01.080 --> 21:04.710
here in Manhattan
at -- at the Trade Center.

21:04.710 --> 21:08.330
We are getting reports
that a part of the tower --

21:08.330 --> 21:09.750
t-the second tower,

21:09.750 --> 21:11.250
the one a bit further
to the south of us --

21:11.250 --> 21:13.250
has collapsed.

21:13.250 --> 21:14.750
We -- We are checking on that.

21:14.750 --> 21:17.790
But obviously, people were,
uh, already at work here

21:17.790 --> 21:20.000
at the Trade Center
when this happened.

21:20.000 --> 21:23.670
We -- We don't know how many
people have been hurt...

21:23.670 --> 21:25.120
[ Crying, sniffles ]

21:26.790 --> 21:27.750
[ Whimpering echoes ]

21:27.750 --> 21:28.960
Claire?

21:28.960 --> 21:31.460
[ Chuckles softly ]

21:31.460 --> 21:32.580
Uh --

21:32.580 --> 21:33.790
Hey!
Hi.

21:33.790 --> 21:35.120
Hi.
Hi.

21:36.750 --> 21:38.540
[ Exhales sharply ]

21:40.170 --> 21:41.500
Uh, may I?

21:41.500 --> 21:43.830
Oh, yeah. Please.
Um, of course.

21:43.830 --> 21:45.210
Hi.
Uh, whiskey, please,

21:45.210 --> 21:47.040
and another glass of wine
for this one.

21:48.710 --> 21:49.960
How are you?

21:49.960 --> 21:51.460
I'm -- I'm good.

21:51.460 --> 21:52.790
It's so good to see you.

21:52.790 --> 21:54.580
Yeah, you too.

21:54.580 --> 21:56.000
I can't believe
we haven't run into each other

21:56.000 --> 21:57.210
at one of these things
before.

21:57.210 --> 21:59.540
Oh, yeah,
I've been practicing in Germany

21:59.540 --> 22:00.920
for the past couple years.

22:00.920 --> 22:02.540
That's exciting.

22:02.540 --> 22:04.330
I'm in North Carolina now.
Which is fine.

22:04.330 --> 22:07.540
Clara and I --
that's my wife.

22:07.540 --> 22:09.210
We are Claire and Clara.

22:09.210 --> 22:10.420
I know. [ Chuckles ]
[ Chuckles ]

22:10.420 --> 22:13.420
We have a small practice
in, uh, her hometown.

22:13.420 --> 22:16.170
Wow. I never thought
you'd leave New York.

22:16.170 --> 22:18.120
Neither did I.

22:18.120 --> 22:21.960
But, you know,
after 9/11, I...

22:21.960 --> 22:24.420
there was just
too much grief there.

22:24.420 --> 22:25.580
In the marrow
of that place.

22:25.580 --> 22:27.330
Mm.

22:27.330 --> 22:29.420
I never saw you again
after she died.

22:29.420 --> 22:30.500
Where did you go?

22:30.500 --> 22:31.330
Afghanistan.

22:32.540 --> 22:33.710
You enlisted?

22:33.710 --> 22:36.710
I know. It's crazy
when I think about it now.

22:36.710 --> 22:38.750
You were practically
a socialist when I met you.

22:38.750 --> 22:43.170
[ Chuckles ] I can't argue that
or totally explain it.

22:43.170 --> 22:45.380
I mean, the closest
I've come

22:45.380 --> 22:48.920
to making any sense of it
is that I-I...

22:48.920 --> 22:50.670
I wanted to support
the soldiers

22:50.670 --> 22:52.920
who were trying to get
the people that killed Allison,

22:52.920 --> 22:55.250
and I-I know that
it's not a straight line,

22:55.250 --> 22:57.460
but at the time,
it was...

22:57.460 --> 22:59.210
Mm.

22:59.210 --> 23:00.960
There wasn't much
that made sense.

23:05.250 --> 23:07.880
It's hard to explain
to people who weren't there.

23:09.500 --> 23:10.880
I miss her.

23:12.250 --> 23:14.080
You miss her?

23:14.080 --> 23:17.830
Every day of every week
of every year of my life.

23:17.830 --> 23:19.460
I don't know why this stuff
always happens to me.

23:19.460 --> 23:21.920
Never to you guys.
Only to me.

23:21.920 --> 23:23.250
I swear to God --
Here's another.

23:23.250 --> 23:25.080
Thank you.

23:25.080 --> 23:26.540
This guy was
clipping his toenails...

23:26.540 --> 23:27.830
[ Laughing ] Oh.

23:27.830 --> 23:30.620
...on the subway
at rush hour.

23:30.620 --> 23:32.040
[ Laughing ]
Only in New York.

23:32.040 --> 23:33.500
[ Laughter ]

23:35.080 --> 23:37.040
Alright,
I gotta go to bed.

23:37.040 --> 23:39.170
Early morning
layout meeting tomorrow.

23:39.170 --> 23:40.330
Boo.

23:40.330 --> 23:41.540
It's only 10:00.

23:41.540 --> 23:43.380
I'm not superhuman
like you two.

23:43.380 --> 23:45.170
I can't survive on
three hours' sleep

23:45.170 --> 23:46.580
and then do surgery
for 12 hours.

23:46.580 --> 23:47.500
16.

23:47.500 --> 23:48.960
Exactly.

23:48.960 --> 23:50.420
Mm.

23:50.420 --> 23:52.210
Please don't stay up
too late.

23:52.210 --> 23:54.500
I need this booty rubbing up
against me in bed.

23:54.500 --> 23:56.040
♪ Till I'd passed
and left them alone ♪

23:56.040 --> 23:57.540
I will be soon.
Okay.

23:57.540 --> 23:58.620
[ Pager beeps ]

23:58.620 --> 24:00.830
No!

24:00.830 --> 24:02.380
[ Whimpering ] No!

24:02.380 --> 24:03.790
I got nothing.
Must be vascular.

24:03.790 --> 24:05.620
Oh, yeah. That's me.

24:05.620 --> 24:07.000
[ Chuckles ]

24:07.000 --> 24:08.290
Okay.

24:08.290 --> 24:10.620
[ Cellphone closes ]

24:10.620 --> 24:12.830
I'll see you later.
Mm.

24:12.830 --> 24:14.620
Please be careful.

24:14.620 --> 24:16.460
Uptown is scary
this time of night.

24:16.460 --> 24:17.830
Alright.

24:17.830 --> 24:19.250
Look after my girl,
Altman.

24:19.250 --> 24:20.420
I'll try.

24:20.420 --> 24:22.040
Night, babe.
Bye.

24:22.040 --> 24:23.750
[ Door closes ]

24:23.750 --> 24:25.960
[ Sighs ]

24:25.960 --> 24:27.380
♪ For the prettiest girl
in the room ♪

24:27.380 --> 24:28.880
[ Clears throat ]

24:28.880 --> 24:30.750
♪ And God help you
if you are a phoenix ♪

24:30.750 --> 24:31.790
You okay?

24:31.790 --> 24:33.710
Yeah. Just, uh...
[ Liquid pours ]

24:33.710 --> 24:35.500
Just tired.

24:35.500 --> 24:36.670
You have to
work tomorrow?

24:36.670 --> 24:37.830
Yeah. All day.

24:37.830 --> 24:39.670
[ Sighs ] Bummer.

24:39.670 --> 24:41.790
I was gonna see if you wanted
to come to work with me tomorrow

24:41.790 --> 24:44.170
and have fancy breakfast
at Windows on the World.

24:44.170 --> 24:46.040
You just said you have
a layout meeting all morning.

24:47.710 --> 24:49.670
So I could have breakfast
with you.

24:49.670 --> 24:51.120
[ Exhales deeply ]

24:55.080 --> 24:57.250
[ Exhales sharply ]

24:57.250 --> 25:02.500
♪♪

25:03.710 --> 25:04.580
I had a baby.

25:05.960 --> 25:07.420
Congratulations!
Thanks.

25:07.420 --> 25:08.460
Uh, pictures, please.

25:08.460 --> 25:10.210
Oh. Yeah, here.

25:12.000 --> 25:13.620
Oh, my goodness!

25:13.620 --> 25:15.330
She's perfect!

25:15.330 --> 25:17.120
Look at those cheeks!

25:17.120 --> 25:18.330
Ohh!
What's her name?

25:18.330 --> 25:19.210
Allison.

25:21.750 --> 25:23.210
That seems odd.

25:23.210 --> 25:24.790
What?

25:24.790 --> 25:26.080
To name your daughter
after --

25:26.080 --> 25:28.040
My best friend?

25:28.040 --> 25:31.460
It's been almost
20 years, Teddy.

25:31.460 --> 25:32.750
You can admit it.

25:32.750 --> 25:33.920
Admit...?

25:36.460 --> 25:39.080
When Allison first told me
that she met this amazing girl

25:39.080 --> 25:41.620
and wanted her
to move in...

25:41.620 --> 25:45.170
I remember thinking,
"She's not a lesbian. Perfect."

25:45.170 --> 25:46.960
In fact,
she made me promise

25:46.960 --> 25:49.000
that I wouldn't
like you better than her

25:49.000 --> 25:50.880
since we're both doctors.

25:50.880 --> 25:52.380
The last thing I expected

25:52.380 --> 25:54.250
was for the two of you
to get together.

25:54.250 --> 26:02.830
♪♪

26:02.830 --> 26:05.500
Tell me again.

26:05.500 --> 26:07.290
You were wearing
your flowered dress

26:07.290 --> 26:09.000
with your combat boots,

26:09.000 --> 26:12.210
and you were riding
a bike.

26:12.210 --> 26:14.210
The one with the basket
in the front...
[ Chuckles ]

26:14.210 --> 26:16.620
...and it was filled
with fake birds.

26:16.620 --> 26:18.960
Oh, my God.
I'm so embarrassed by me.

26:18.960 --> 26:20.920
Shh. I'm telling it.

26:20.920 --> 26:21.920
Okay.
Okay.

26:21.920 --> 26:23.330
And then you almost hit me

26:23.330 --> 26:24.960
because I was
crossing the street

26:24.960 --> 26:26.330
and I was looking
at a map,

26:26.330 --> 26:27.790
and then I looked up,
and I said --

26:27.790 --> 26:30.170
"Get those birds
out of my way, Pollyanna!"

26:30.170 --> 26:32.040
I was stressed.
I was a first year attending.

26:33.830 --> 26:35.620
You were mean.

26:35.620 --> 26:37.580
And beautiful.

26:37.580 --> 26:40.170
And I feel desperately
in love with you on sight.

26:40.170 --> 26:41.670
You did not.

26:41.670 --> 26:43.120
Okay, I kinda
hated you at first.

26:43.120 --> 26:44.830
[ Chuckles ]
You were in the bike lane.

26:44.830 --> 26:46.880
[ Laughing ]
I know. I'm sorry.

26:49.380 --> 26:51.750
But I bought you
a bagel anyway.

26:53.120 --> 26:55.330
I'm so lucky you did.

26:55.330 --> 27:04.380
♪♪

27:04.380 --> 27:05.380
Allison.

27:05.380 --> 27:06.210
Mm.

27:07.790 --> 27:09.080
I can't --

27:10.960 --> 27:13.710
I can't keep doing this.

27:13.710 --> 27:14.750
Kissing me?

27:14.750 --> 27:16.790
No, I just --
I can't keep sneaking around

27:16.790 --> 27:18.120
and lying to Claire.

27:18.120 --> 27:20.080
She's our best friend.

27:20.080 --> 27:22.040
Oh.

27:22.040 --> 27:24.080
I know.
Oh. I know.

27:25.670 --> 27:26.920
I'm an awful person.

27:26.920 --> 27:28.960
No.

27:28.960 --> 27:32.040
You are the best person.

27:32.040 --> 27:39.830
♪♪

27:39.830 --> 27:41.250
I'm telling her.

27:42.460 --> 27:43.620
I'm telling her tomorrow.

27:43.620 --> 27:44.960
Then what?

27:44.960 --> 27:46.960
W-We all come home
to the apartment that we share

27:46.960 --> 27:49.250
and help her pack up
and move out?

27:51.960 --> 27:53.620
Or we could move out.

27:53.620 --> 27:55.920
And then she's stuck
with three shares of the rent?

27:55.920 --> 27:57.290
[ Sighs ]

27:57.290 --> 27:59.750
You're right. I know.

28:02.290 --> 28:04.710
But I can't keep
lying to her, either.

28:05.960 --> 28:08.040
[ Sighs ]
I love her.

28:11.250 --> 28:12.710
And I love you more.

28:12.710 --> 28:14.040
Don't say that.

28:17.830 --> 28:19.170
Okay, say it again.

28:20.580 --> 28:22.420
I love you more.

28:25.500 --> 28:27.120
I love you more.

28:30.080 --> 28:31.080
[ Smooches ]

28:31.080 --> 28:33.540
Mm.
I love you more.

28:33.540 --> 28:34.960
[ Sighs ]

28:34.960 --> 28:36.960
♪♪

28:36.960 --> 28:38.210
[ Exhales sharply ]

28:40.250 --> 28:41.620
[ Exhales sharply,
echoing ]

28:41.620 --> 28:43.250
How long did you know?

28:43.250 --> 28:44.620
I suspected for months.

28:44.620 --> 28:46.750
Mm.

28:46.750 --> 28:48.580
Did you ever stop and think
about what it would do to me,

28:48.580 --> 28:49.790
or did you just not care?

28:49.790 --> 28:51.790
No, it tore me up,
Claire. I --

28:51.790 --> 28:53.330
But not enough to stop.

28:56.620 --> 28:59.710
I requested her phone records
after she died.

28:59.710 --> 29:04.920
I kept trying to imagine her
in those last minutes.

29:04.920 --> 29:07.920
"What did she do?
What did she see?
Was she in pain?"

29:09.080 --> 29:11.290
So I got
her phone records,

29:11.290 --> 29:15.420
from that -- that clunky
little Nokia she had.

29:15.420 --> 29:17.880
And I found out that
you were the last person

29:17.880 --> 29:19.250
she tried to call.

29:20.460 --> 29:23.210
At 8:57 a.m.

29:23.210 --> 29:26.830
On September 11, 2001.

29:26.830 --> 29:30.380
Allison Robin Brown tried
to call you, Teddy Altman,

29:30.380 --> 29:34.670
as the Twin Towers
fell around her,

29:34.670 --> 29:36.380
as she --

29:36.380 --> 29:39.170
as she fell
out of the sky.

29:39.170 --> 29:40.670
Not me.

29:40.670 --> 29:41.500
Not her parents.

29:41.500 --> 29:43.170
You.

29:43.170 --> 29:44.830
That's how I found out.

29:44.830 --> 29:50.170
♪♪

29:50.170 --> 29:53.420
She was
the love of my life.

29:55.080 --> 29:56.880
And you were
the love of hers.

29:56.880 --> 30:02.880
♪♪

30:02.880 --> 30:04.250
Take care, Teddy.

30:04.250 --> 30:07.290
♪♪

30:14.120 --> 30:16.210
There was this one time
you let me scrub in

30:16.210 --> 30:18.210
on a piggyback transplant.

30:18.210 --> 30:20.670
Oh, my God.
I was so nervous.

30:20.670 --> 30:23.250
I was afraid I was gonna drop
the donor heart on the OR floor.

30:23.250 --> 30:24.880
[ Chuckles ]

30:24.880 --> 30:26.670
This is so crazy.

30:26.670 --> 30:29.420
'Cause that is how I felt
every single time I saw you.

30:31.120 --> 30:33.750
Except in the OR, because
in there, I'm a superhero.

30:33.750 --> 30:37.880
But in regular life,
I am a neurotic mess.

30:37.880 --> 30:39.620
I do not see that.

30:39.620 --> 30:42.080
I guess...

30:42.080 --> 30:43.540
I'm not.

30:43.540 --> 30:45.380
With you.

30:45.380 --> 30:47.620
I mean, at least not
for the last few hours.

30:47.620 --> 30:48.880
Mm.

30:48.880 --> 30:50.710
[ Cellphone alarm ringing ]

30:53.620 --> 30:55.460
[ Ringing stops ]
For the last 12 hours?

30:55.460 --> 30:57.710
Is it morning?!

30:57.710 --> 30:59.670
Oh, my God!

31:02.710 --> 31:03.960
[ Gasps ]

31:03.960 --> 31:06.000
Oh, look.
The sunrise.

31:06.000 --> 31:07.000
It's time for your run.

31:07.000 --> 31:08.920
[ Laughs ]

31:11.380 --> 31:12.920
Which talks
are you going to?

31:12.920 --> 31:16.830
Um..."Bioethics
in Crisis Zones"

31:16.830 --> 31:19.580
and "Innovations in Pathology:
Presenting" --

31:19.580 --> 31:21.040
The PATH pen!

31:21.040 --> 31:22.460
That's Richard's talk.

31:22.460 --> 31:23.750
And Richard is...?

31:23.750 --> 31:26.000
My biological dad.
Remember? I told you.

31:26.000 --> 31:28.830
Oh, right. Yeah.
Richard.

31:28.830 --> 31:31.040
So, is it gonna be weird
if I meet this man

31:31.040 --> 31:32.620
on what amounts
to our first date?

31:32.620 --> 31:34.460
Yeah.
Incredibly weird.

31:34.460 --> 31:36.330
[ Chuckles ]
Yeah.

31:36.330 --> 31:39.460
But everything about this night
has been weird.

31:39.460 --> 31:40.670
Weird and...

31:40.670 --> 31:42.380
Mm.

31:42.380 --> 31:44.170
...perfect.

31:46.750 --> 31:48.540
♪♪

31:48.540 --> 31:49.830
Mm.

31:52.670 --> 31:54.460
Conference.

31:56.460 --> 31:57.540
Advancement.

31:57.540 --> 31:59.250
Mm-hmm.

31:59.250 --> 32:00.880
Expanding our minds.

32:00.880 --> 32:03.000
Right.
Mm-hmm.

32:03.000 --> 32:04.960
Surgical.

32:06.000 --> 32:07.790
Innovation.

32:07.790 --> 32:09.290
Technology.

32:09.290 --> 32:11.000
[ Both chuckle ]

32:11.000 --> 32:17.210
♪♪

32:17.210 --> 32:19.080
Mmmmmmm.

32:19.080 --> 32:20.290
Hi there.

32:20.290 --> 32:22.500
[ Chuckles ]
Mm.

32:22.500 --> 32:24.000
Good morning, Cleopatra.

32:24.000 --> 32:25.920
[ Both chuckle ]

32:25.920 --> 32:27.210
Oh. There's coffee.

32:27.210 --> 32:28.960
Mm.
[ Chuckles ]

32:28.960 --> 32:31.080
You know,
maybe it's okay

32:31.080 --> 32:32.620
that we fight
like cats and dogs.

32:32.620 --> 32:34.000
[ Chuckles ]

32:34.000 --> 32:35.290
Maybe
if we stopped fighting,

32:35.290 --> 32:37.420
that's when we need
to start to worry.

32:40.580 --> 32:42.380
Now...

32:42.380 --> 32:46.540
healthy cells
never stop dividing.

32:46.540 --> 32:48.830
It's not until they're harmed
in -- in some way

32:48.830 --> 32:50.460
that growth stops.

32:52.380 --> 32:55.620
But cancer cells...

32:55.620 --> 32:59.920
they keep growing even if
the conditions aren't ideal.

32:59.920 --> 33:03.500
Baby, please tell me you're
not comparing us to cancer.

33:03.500 --> 33:07.710
Okay, the problem isn't that
cancer cells keep growing.

33:07.710 --> 33:12.080
It's that
the good cells...stop.

33:12.080 --> 33:13.620
♪ All these places... ♪

33:13.620 --> 33:15.460
Catherine,
you are a genius.

33:15.460 --> 33:16.670
[ Laughs ]
Ohh!

33:16.670 --> 33:18.750
[ Both laugh ]

33:18.750 --> 33:20.210
You have to make
that presentation

33:20.210 --> 33:21.420
in a couple of hours.

33:21.420 --> 33:22.620
You better hurry up.

33:22.620 --> 33:25.580
Okay, I'm going
as fast as I can.

33:25.580 --> 33:29.920
♪ I can make my first steps ♪

33:29.920 --> 33:31.620
♪ As a child... ♪

33:31.620 --> 33:33.080
Hey.

33:33.080 --> 33:34.920
Hey.

33:34.920 --> 33:36.960
Do I smell like sex?

33:36.960 --> 33:38.210
I mean, I took a shower,
but I just --

33:38.210 --> 33:40.250
I'm not sure
I got it all off.

33:40.250 --> 33:42.710
Do you really want me
to smell you?

33:42.710 --> 33:44.330
I just never knew
it was possible

33:44.330 --> 33:47.170
to like someone so much
that you know so little.

33:47.170 --> 33:53.250
♪ Roof of my mouth
as I lie to you ♪

33:53.250 --> 33:57.330
♪♪

33:57.330 --> 34:00.620
You know what? I'm, um --
I-I'll catch up to you, okay?

34:00.620 --> 34:03.040
♪ ...doesn't mean ♪

34:05.170 --> 34:10.080
♪ I didn't enjoy it
at the time ♪

34:10.080 --> 34:11.750
Claire,
I owe you an apology.

34:11.750 --> 34:13.000
No, you don't.

34:13.000 --> 34:15.040
I had too many free drinks
last night.

34:15.040 --> 34:17.170
It was 20 years ago.
Bygones.

34:17.170 --> 34:20.000
It's not bygones.
I mean, not even a little bit.

34:20.000 --> 34:22.250
And...we both know it.

34:25.710 --> 34:27.790
I met the father of my daughter
in Afghanistan

34:27.790 --> 34:29.330
after Allison died,

34:29.330 --> 34:31.540
and he saved me
from a grief so huge,

34:31.540 --> 34:34.000
I probably
would have let it kill me.

34:34.000 --> 34:37.750
And for years, I loved him
so much, I felt guilty.

34:37.750 --> 34:40.920
Guilty for loving him
half as much as I loved Allison.

34:40.920 --> 34:43.790
Guilty because he was
with someone else.

34:43.790 --> 34:45.080
And guilty because...

34:48.250 --> 34:50.790
...because maybe
I wasn't capable

34:50.790 --> 34:53.170
of letting someone
love me fully.

34:55.210 --> 34:57.210
And Allison
did love me, yes.

34:59.290 --> 35:01.040
But she loved you,
too, Claire.

35:02.380 --> 35:04.790
Allison was in love
with the both of us.

35:04.790 --> 35:06.500
And at the time,
I didn't believe it.

35:06.500 --> 35:08.210
I --

35:08.210 --> 35:11.880
I thought no one could love
more than one person at once.

35:11.880 --> 35:14.880
I-I thought --

35:14.880 --> 35:18.540
I thought love couldn't
be divided like that.

35:18.540 --> 35:20.290
But now I do.

35:20.290 --> 35:22.170
I believe it.

35:22.170 --> 35:24.880
And I am sorry
for the lies,

35:24.880 --> 35:27.920
and I'm sorry
for the betrayal.

35:27.920 --> 35:31.460
[ Voice breaking ]
I was a bad friend,
and I was selfish.

35:31.460 --> 35:35.460
And I never, ever meant
to hurt you.

35:35.460 --> 35:42.330
♪ I promise
I'll do anything you ask ♪

35:42.330 --> 35:45.290
I could never stay mad
at anybody for loving Allison.

35:45.290 --> 35:47.380
♪♪

35:47.380 --> 35:49.250
She's Allison.

35:49.250 --> 35:58.620
♪♪

35:58.620 --> 36:00.170
[ Slurps ]

36:00.170 --> 36:01.460
Ah.

36:01.460 --> 36:03.620
Honey. I think
I've cracked it.

36:03.620 --> 36:05.170
That's great, dear.

36:05.170 --> 36:06.380
Alright. Okay.

36:06.380 --> 36:09.040
So, here we go.
Um...

36:09.040 --> 36:10.420
"Thank you very much.

36:10.420 --> 36:14.250
I can't tell you what an honor
it is to be here."

36:14.250 --> 36:15.880
Catherine: Well, wait.
Why don't you make it funny?

36:15.880 --> 36:17.500
Make a joke of it.

36:17.500 --> 36:19.210
Oh. That's a good point.
That's a good point.

36:19.210 --> 36:20.540
Joke. Yeah. Okay.

36:20.540 --> 36:22.290
Um...

36:22.290 --> 36:25.250
[ Keyboard clacking ]
"Also, I can't tell you
how many times

36:25.250 --> 36:28.580
I've rewritten
this presentation."

36:28.580 --> 36:29.500
[ Chuckles ]

36:35.210 --> 36:36.290
Nervous?

36:36.290 --> 36:37.500
Energized.

36:37.500 --> 36:38.750
[ Chuckles ]

36:38.750 --> 36:40.420
Break a leg.

36:40.420 --> 36:41.420
Okay.

36:47.790 --> 36:49.750
Look at you.

36:49.750 --> 36:50.920
Come back to Boston.

36:50.920 --> 36:52.170
What?

36:52.170 --> 36:53.500
With me.
Come back with me.

36:53.500 --> 36:55.460
You want me to...

36:55.460 --> 36:58.210
move back to Boston
to be with you?

36:58.210 --> 36:59.420
Yes.

36:59.420 --> 37:01.580
Or I'll move to Seattle.

37:01.580 --> 37:04.210
I know. It's crazy.

37:04.210 --> 37:06.120
But this happens,
right?

37:06.120 --> 37:08.670
I mean, sometimes you just
meet somebody and you know.

37:09.960 --> 37:12.000
And, look,
after my mom died,

37:12.000 --> 37:14.120
I-I've been a little bit...

37:14.120 --> 37:16.120
you know...
seize the day.

37:16.120 --> 37:17.920
"O Captain! My Captain!"

37:17.920 --> 37:19.540
"Dead Poets Society."
"Dead Poets Society."

37:19.540 --> 37:20.880
It's my second favorite --
It's my second favorite --

37:22.380 --> 37:24.670
[ Clears throat ]
So, I'm -- I'm a person who --

37:24.670 --> 37:26.290
I need time
to make decisions.

37:26.290 --> 37:29.750
I need to weigh and measure
and make spreadsheets.

37:29.750 --> 37:30.750
Got it.

37:30.750 --> 37:31.920
Okay. Okay.
Okay.

37:31.920 --> 37:33.500
Take as much time
as you need.

37:33.500 --> 37:34.830
Get a focus group
together.

37:34.830 --> 37:36.460
[ Laughs ]
Do a study.
Write a paper.

37:36.460 --> 37:37.580
Okay.

37:37.580 --> 37:39.380
I just don't think that
I'm gonna feel

37:39.380 --> 37:41.670
any differently about this
in a few hours

37:41.670 --> 37:43.540
or a few months.

37:43.540 --> 37:45.830
But...

37:45.830 --> 37:47.290
you do you.

37:47.290 --> 37:53.210
♪♪

37:53.210 --> 37:59.080
♪♪

37:59.080 --> 38:01.250
[ Applause ]

38:07.330 --> 38:08.790
Over three decades

38:08.790 --> 38:12.710
as a surgeon, teacher,
and chief of surgery

38:12.710 --> 38:15.120
at Seattle's Grey-Sloan
Memorial Hospital...

38:15.120 --> 38:18.000
Jackson!
Nothing's showing yet.

38:18.000 --> 38:20.210
I know, Ma. Calm down.

38:20.210 --> 38:21.960
You said this was
gonna work.

38:21.960 --> 38:23.080
Will you sit down,
please?

38:23.080 --> 38:25.040
[ Sighs ]
I'm working on it.

38:26.290 --> 38:29.750
Our next speaker has
built a sterling reputation.

38:29.750 --> 38:31.250
In Washington and abroad...

38:31.250 --> 38:33.580
How do you know
how to do this stuff?

38:33.580 --> 38:35.710
Everyone knows
how to do this stuff, Mom.

38:37.420 --> 38:40.620
...and his medical judgment
is second to none.

38:40.620 --> 38:44.920
Please join me in welcoming
my colleague and friend

38:44.920 --> 38:46.460
Dr. Richard Webber.

38:46.460 --> 38:48.000
[ Cheers and applause ]
Whoo-hoo!

38:48.000 --> 38:49.830
I think I just heard
Auntie Maggie say "Whoo-hoo!"

38:49.830 --> 38:50.830
Me too.

38:50.830 --> 38:53.040
[ Applause continues ]

38:53.040 --> 38:54.880
Oh, did it start?

38:54.880 --> 38:56.380
He's going on
right now.

38:56.380 --> 38:57.170
I'm sorry.

38:58.920 --> 39:00.830
[ Applause continues ]

39:00.830 --> 39:02.670
Thank you so much, Cynthia.

39:05.000 --> 39:08.250
I can't tell you what an honor
it is to be here.

39:08.250 --> 39:10.210
Also, I can't tell you
how many times

39:10.210 --> 39:12.580
I've rewritten
this presentation.

39:12.580 --> 39:15.040
[ Laughter ]

39:15.040 --> 39:17.080
I've worked hard...

39:17.080 --> 39:18.420
He looks good.
[ Clears throat ]

39:18.420 --> 39:20.170
...to develop the PATH pen...

39:20.170 --> 39:21.960
I'm just pointing it out.
...but...

39:21.960 --> 39:24.040
that's not why I'm here anymore.

39:24.040 --> 39:27.790
Because this morning, with
my brilliant wife's help...

39:27.790 --> 39:29.710
What's that?
...I have figured out...

39:29.710 --> 39:31.000
[ Chuckles ]

39:31.000 --> 39:33.580
...how to cure cancer.

39:33.580 --> 39:35.670
[ Audience murmurs ]

39:35.670 --> 39:39.040
Now, good cells need
favorable conditions,

39:39.040 --> 39:41.080
nurturing
and loving conditions.

39:43.120 --> 39:45.460
What is he doing?
What is happening?

39:45.460 --> 39:46.460
I don't know.

39:46.460 --> 39:48.170
Think of everything
in -- in your life.

39:48.170 --> 39:51.790
Every moment, every cell,
every atom

39:51.790 --> 39:56.380
as having a simple positive
or negative charge,

39:56.380 --> 39:59.790
which is just...you know...

39:59.790 --> 40:02.460
good or bad, right?

40:02.460 --> 40:03.540
Something is wrong.

40:03.540 --> 40:05.540
Um...

40:05.540 --> 40:07.750
Okay, uh...let's see.

40:07.750 --> 40:08.960
Um...

40:08.960 --> 40:10.620
Uh-huh.

40:10.620 --> 40:11.920
Ah. Okay.

40:11.920 --> 40:14.620
So, um, now,
it's not fair to blame

40:14.620 --> 40:20.080
the environment or toxins
o-or -- or family history.

40:20.080 --> 40:21.830
Um...

40:21.830 --> 40:24.210
cells need apologies.

40:24.210 --> 40:25.830
[ Whispering ]
Dear Lord.

40:25.830 --> 40:27.210
He's drunk.
They need to know on
an elemental level

40:27.210 --> 40:29.170
that we are sorry.

40:29.170 --> 40:30.540
What's
Uncle Richard saying?

40:30.540 --> 40:31.790
I don't know.

40:31.790 --> 40:32.830
Will you go grab my phone?

40:34.790 --> 40:36.000
Um...

40:36.000 --> 40:38.420
[ Chuckles ]
Okay. Um...

40:38.420 --> 40:39.750
Uh...

40:39.750 --> 40:42.170
Circle!
I-I need the circle!

40:42.170 --> 40:43.380
No.

40:43.380 --> 40:45.620
Here we go. Where --

40:45.620 --> 40:47.000
Okay, I'm --

40:47.000 --> 40:48.880
I need a...circle.

40:48.880 --> 40:50.330
Ah.

40:50.330 --> 40:53.380
So, um, if we divide
a circle into fourths

40:53.380 --> 40:56.290
and then we remove
one of those fourths...

40:56.290 --> 40:58.000
We have to get him
down from there.

40:58.000 --> 40:59.500
I'll call for
a gurney and oxygen.

40:59.500 --> 41:01.790
...now a third of --
of the remainder.

41:01.790 --> 41:03.500
Um...you see?

41:03.500 --> 41:07.000
Okay, a-and then
all of the pieces will continue

41:07.000 --> 41:08.830
to make -- make the whole,

41:08.830 --> 41:11.580
eh, if the whole
is filled with --

41:11.580 --> 41:13.040
with, uh, evidence.

41:13.040 --> 41:15.380
Now, this evidence that
we're talking about is --

41:15.380 --> 41:16.460
Maggie: Richard,
Richard, Richard.

41:16.460 --> 41:17.880
Richard. Okay?

41:17.880 --> 41:19.500
We're gonna take you home.
You're not feeling well.

41:19.500 --> 41:21.120
Uh, you know what?
I'm -- I'm fine.

41:21.120 --> 41:22.580
You're -- You're --
You're embarrassing me.

41:22.580 --> 41:24.960
I'm -- I'm sorry,
ladies and gentlemen.

41:24.960 --> 41:26.920
But the historic
illusion of, uh --

41:26.920 --> 41:27.830
Please, Richard.

41:27.830 --> 41:29.750
[ Audience murmuring ]

41:29.750 --> 41:31.120
W-Who are you?

41:31.120 --> 41:33.040
It's me.
It's -- It's Maggie.

41:34.830 --> 41:36.670
Um...
